Introduction

This Rmarkdown file performs data science steps on raw anonymized Dengue incidence data from Ho Chi Minh City and Hanoi, between 2017-2022. These steps will help you understand the raw data and how we opted to work with it. The data comes as 2 folders, one for Hanoi and one for Ho Chi Minh City, which we have removed most personal identifiable information, the rest will be removed in this file.

c. Type conversion

  • Here we will convert dates and other numerical values from character vectors into its intended data type.
  • First we will check if the dates are cleanly formatted.
# convert character vectors to date objects
# extract years as well
incidence_df %<>%
  mutate(
    across(
      c(
        dob, date_admitted, date_symptom_onset,
        date_discharged_transferred_died
      ),
      .fns = dmy
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    year_dob = year(dob),
    year_admitted = year(date_admitted),
    year_symptom_onset = year(date_symptom_onset),
    year_discharged_transferred_died = year(date_discharged_transferred_died)
  )

incidence_df %>%
  select(
    year_dob,
    year_admitted,
    year_symptom_onset,
    year_discharged_transferred_died
  ) %>%
  summary()

  • From the data summary, we can see that most of the data (data within IQR) are correct, e.g. year of birth range from 1984-2007, and year of admission range from 2018-2021. Though, there are some incorrectly values in the minimum and maximums.
  • Let’s clean this data up. First, we will see how much of the data is out of the range. The ranges will be defined as
    • [2016, 2023] for admission years, as well as symptom onset years and discharged/transferred/died years
    • [1923, 2023] for birth years (implying the maximum patient age we’re going to look at is 100 years old)
incidence_df %>%
  mutate(
    is_in_range = case_when(
      year_admitted > 2023 ~ "out range",
      year_admitted < 2016 ~ "out range",
      year_symptom_onset > 2023 ~ "out range",
      year_symptom_onset < 2016 ~ "out range",
      year_discharged_transferred_died > 2023 ~ "out range",
      year_discharged_transferred_died < 2016 ~ "out range",
      .default = "in range"
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(is_in_range) %>%
  summarise(total = n())
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   is_in_range  total
##   <chr>        <int>
## 1 in range    364484
## 2 out range      123
  • For admission, sympton onset and discharged/transferred/died years, only 123 rows are outside of the predefined range. Since this is miniscule compared to the data size, we’ll remove these rows from further analysis.
incidence_df %>%
  count(year_dob) %>%
  mutate(
    is_in_range = case_when(
      year_dob < 1923 ~ "out range",
      year_dob > 2023 ~ "out range",
      .default = "in range"
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(is_in_range) %>%
  summarise(total = sum(n))
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   is_in_range  total
##   <chr>        <int>
## 1 in range    364458
## 2 out range      149
  • Same story for birth years, only 149 rows are outside of the predefined range. We’ll also remove these rows from further analysis.
incidence_df %<>%
  filter(
    year_dob <= 2023, year_dob >= 1923
  ) %>%
  filter(
    year_admitted <= 2023, year_admitted >= 2016
  ) %>%
  filter(
    (year_symptom_onset <= 2023 & year_symptom_onset >= 2016) | is.na(year_symptom_onset)
  ) %>%
  filter(
    (year_discharged_transferred_died <= 2023 &
      year_discharged_transferred_died >= 2016) |
      is.na(year_discharged_transferred_died)
  )
  • Now, we have converted date data from character vectors into date objects, while also went on a little detour to clean the date data.

Upon further manual inspection, it seems like these duplication are a result of file duplication, i.e. some folder has 2 incidence files that are exactly the same.

  • We also found there are ID duplicates where the duplication only happens in the ID of the incidence. We hypothesize that this might be because the surveillance system assigns each patient a unique ID of their own. Some of these cases are either second infections, patients being referred/transferred to another treating unit, or just simply updates from past incidence reports.
incidence_df %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  summarise(dupes = n()) %>%
  filter(dupes > 1) %>%
  count(dupes)

  • Above you can see the count of number of duplicates. Curiously, we have an ID where it is duplicated 237 times. This requires further investigation.
  • Before that, we will need to check if any of these duplicates are secondary infections. The criteria for records to be considered as secondary infections would be that they use the same ID, and has more than 30 days between reported times. Records that have the same ID but were reported within 30 days of each other would be considered an update of the first incidence report, not a new separate incidence.
# parse `reported_time` into a datetime object
incidence_df %<>%
  mutate(
    reported_time = parse_date_time2(reported_time, "HMSdmY")
  )

# dataframe of duplicates with date difference based on time of incidence report
datediff_df <- incidence_df %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  filter(n() > 1) %>%
  arrange(reported_time) %>%
  mutate(
    reported_time_diff = difftime(
      reported_time,
      lag(reported_time),
      units = "days"
    ) %>%
      as.integer()
  )

datediff_df %>%
  filter(reported_time_diff > 30)

  • From this, we also discover that there are also incidence updates for secondary infections. So, to solve this we will
    • group all reported incidences together by ID, then split them into groups depends on the time of report.
    • This will split first infection and its case updates into one group, and the second infection and its case updates into another group.
    • From these groups, we will then extract the latest report only, and use it to represent the incidence as a whole.
    • This is not the most effective way but it is a good way to perform deduplications against incidence updates, as well as generalized enough to account for tertiary and quarternary infections. The remaining incidence reports will be unique for each patient and each infection.

A visualization of this problem: 

cat("Before duplication removal:", nrow(incidence_df), "rows \n")
## Before duplication removal: 333117 rows
incidence_df %<>%
  arrange(id, date_admitted) %>%
  mutate(
    group = cumsum(
      c(1, diff(date_admitted) > 30 | diff(id %>% as.numeric()) != 0)
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(id, group) %>%
  slice_tail(n = 1) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-group)

shape_lvl1 %<>%

  • Now we make a function to check which units are giving incorrect coordinates. We will do this by generating the coordinates (called geocoding) of the reported units. Then we use those coordinates to check against the polygons of the provinces.
coordinate_check <- function(data) {
  ## generate coordinates for each unique reported unit
  data %<>%
    unite(
      "reported_unit_address", reported_unit:reported_unit_province,
      sep = ", ", remove = F, na.rm = TRUE
    ) %>%
    tidygeocoder::geocode(
      reported_unit_address,
      method = "arcgis", lat = lat, lon = lon
    ) %>%
    select(
      "reported_unit_address", "reported_unit",
      "reported_unit_province", "lat", "lon"
    ) %>%
    unique(by = "reported_unit")

  ## convert data into spatial feature
  point <- st_as_sf(data, coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = st_crs(4326))

  ## Check if the coordinates generate from tidygeocoder::geocode is within the province provided
  ls <- as.data.frame(st_contains(shape_lvl1, point, sparse = FALSE))
  names(ls) <- point$reported_unit_address

  ls1 <- data.frame(r1 = point$reported_unit_address, t(ls))
  names(ls1)[2:64] <- shape_lvl1$NAME_1
  ls1 %<>% mutate(province = data$reported_unit_province)
  ls1$province_check <- apply(ls1[-1], 1, function(x) names(which(x == TRUE)), simplify = FALSE)
  ls1 %<>% mutate(check = if_else(province == province_check, TRUE, FALSE))

  ls2 <- ls1 %>% filter(check == FALSE)
  ls2
}

2. Extract information from notes

  • notes is a free text column where nurses and doctors add more info about the patients, e.g. parents’ information of child patients, symptoms, and, most importantly, measurements such as platelet count, hematocrit, and severity classification. Platelet count and hematocrit can also help gauge the severity of the dengue fever. We will achieve this through the power of regular expression.

2.1. ICD-10 severity classification

  • The regex string below will capture the severity classification according to Vietnam’s ICD-10. Another regex string will capture most if not all mentions of platelet and hematocrit in the notes. It will split the capture into groups with the measure, value and unit used into different columns.

Want to understand how the regex string works? Try them with regex101.com!

  • The regex strings will be encapsulated with r"{ }", which are R raw character constants.

  • Before we start, we’ll replace all the whitespace escape characters in notes to a normal space character.

incidence_df %<>% mutate(notes = str_replace_all(notes, c(r"{[\r\n\t\f\v]}" = "\ ")))
  • First, let’s see how many incidences have an ICD-10 classification in its notes
icd10_regex <- r"{(a9\d+)[.,]*(\w?\d*)}"

icd10_rows <- incidence_df %>%
  filter(grepl(icd10_regex, notes)) %>%
  select(id, severity, notes)

##  5 a91   "c"        297
##  6 a91   "c1"       143
##  7 a91   "c2"        12
##  8 a91   "d"          1
##  9 a913  "a"          1
## 10 a97   ""           2

  • For Dengue, the main ICD-10 class is a91 with a as the most common subclass (Dengue fever). a97 is the new classification code which is not commonly used in the data, hence we’ll convert them to a91. And since they don’t have a subclass as well, we will impute with subclass a.

  • There are 6 subclasses: <empty>, 1, a, b, c, c1, c2, and d. Subclasses a, b, c, c1, and c2 are official subclasses that describe the severity of DF. Subclass d does not seem to exist and only has 1 record, it will be changed to subclass a. The same will be done to subclasses <empty> and 1.

icd10_rows %<>%
  mutate(
    class = case_match(
      class, "a97" ~ "a91",
      .default = class
    ),
    subclass = case_match(
      subclass,
      c("", "1", "d") ~ "a",
      .default = subclass
    ),
    full = paste0(class, ".", subclass)
  )

icd10_rows %>%
  group_by(full, class, subclass) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## # A tibble: 6 × 4
## # Groups:   full, class [6]
##   full   class subclass count
##   <chr>  <chr> <chr>    <int>
## 1 a91.a  a91   a         5080
## 2 a91.b  a91   b         2446
## 3 a91.c  a91   c          297
## 4 a91.c1 a91   c1         143
## 5 a91.c2 a91   c2          12
## 6 a913.a a913  a            1
  • Now, with the ICD-10 classifications, we will use them to impute the missing severity data. We are going to use the following table

dengue severity classification table

to match between the severity and its ICD-10 code.

icd10_rows %<>% mutate(
  severity = case_when(
    subclass == "a" ~ "dengue",
    subclass == "b" ~ "dengue with warning signs",
    subclass %in% c("c", "c1", "c2") ~ "severe dengue",
    .default = severity
  )
)
icd10_rows

  • And then we will copy the severity back over to the main dataframe using record IDs.
# Before
incidence_df %>%
  group_by(severity) %>%
  summarise(total = n())
## # A tibble: 4 × 2
##   severity                   total
##   <chr>                      <int>
## 1 dengue                     67304
## 2 dengue with warning signs   9085
## 3 severe dengue               1892
## 4 <NA>                      243622
# Impute `severity` based on ICD-10 classifications extracted from `notes`
incidence_df %<>%
  left_join(
    icd10_rows %>% select(id, severity),
    by = "id"
  ) %>%
  mutate(severity = ifelse(is.na(severity.x), severity.y, severity.x), .keep = "unused")

# After
incidence_df %>%
  group_by(severity) %>%
  summarise(total = n())

Year-age rolling quantiles (1-month)

weeks <- incidence_df %>%
  filter(
    reported_unit_province %in% c("tp. h.c.m", "hà nội")
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    week_admitted = floor_date(date_admitted, "week")
  ) %>%
  select(age, week_admitted, reported_unit_province)

window_width <- 52 # in weeks
rolling_step <- 4 # in weeks

left_ticks <- seq(
  floor_date(ymd("2017-01-01"), "week") - weeks(floor(window_width / 2)),
  floor_date(ymd("2023-01-01"), "week") - weeks(floor(window_width / 2)),
  by = sprintf("%d weeks", rolling_step)
)

rolling_quantile_df <- tibble(
  center_week = Date(),
  quant5 = double(),
  quant25 = double(),
  quant50 = double(),
  quant75 = double(),
  quant100 = double(),
  reported_unit_province = character()
)

for (ltick in as.list(left_ticks)) {
  low <- ltick
  high <- ltick + weeks(window_width)

  quant_w_unit <- weeks %>%
    filter(week_admitted < high, week_admitted > low) %>%
    select(age, reported_unit_province) %>%
    group_by(reported_unit_province) %>%
    summarise(
      quant5 = quantile(age, probs = .05),
      quant25 = quantile(age, probs = .25),
      quant50 = quantile(age, probs = .5),
      quant75 = quantile(age, probs = .75),
      quant100 = quantile(age, probs = 1)
    ) %>%
    mutate(center_week = low + dweeks(7))

  rolling_quantile_df %<>% bind_rows(quant_w_unit)
}


rolling_quantile_df %>%
  pivot_longer(!c(center_week, reported_unit_province)) %>%
  mutate(name = factor(
    name,
    levels = c("quant5", "quant25", "quant50", "quant75", "quant100")
  )) %>%
  ggplot(
    aes(x = center_week, y = value, group = name, color = name)
  ) +
  geom_line() +
  ylab("Age") +
  xlab("Time") +
  labs(color = "Quantiles") +
  scale_color_discrete(
    labels = c(
      "quant100" = "100% quantile",
      "quant75" = "75% quantile",
      "quant50" = "50% quantile",
      "quant25" = "25% quantile",
      "quant5" = "5% quantile"
    ),
    limits = rev
  ) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 year", date_labels = "%Y") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 10)) +
  facet_wrap(~reported_unit_province)

    time_diff = difftime(reported_time, date_admitted, units = "days") %>% as.double() %>% ceiling()
  ) %>%
  select(id, time_diff) %>%
  filter(time_diff < 14.1, time_diff > 0) %>%
  group_by(time_diff) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(csum = cumsum(count), total = incidence_df %>% nrow())

csum_df %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = time_diff, y = csum / total)) +
  xlab("Number of days since admission to reported") +
  ylab("Proportion of cases reported") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, 14)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)) +
  geom_text(
    x = 14,
    aes(
      y = max(csum) / total + 0.03,
      label = sprintf("%.2f%%", max(csum) / total * 100)
    )
  )

Incidence reported severity against reported condition

incidence_df %>%
  mutate(
    severity = case_when(is.na(severity) ~ "NA", .default = severity),
    severity = factor(
      severity,
      levels = c("dengue", "dengue with warning signs", "severe dengue", "NA")
    )
  ) %>%
  count(current_condition, severity) %>%
  group_by(current_condition) %>%
  mutate(grouped_total = sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(
    aes(
      y = reorder(severity, -as.numeric(severity)),
      x = n / grouped_total,
      group = current_condition
    )
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~current_condition) +
  scale_x_continuous("Proportion of reported severity per group total") +
  scale_y_discrete("Reported severity")
